{"url": "https://www.ics.uci.edu/~kobsa/courses/INF231/17F/syllabus.htm", "content": "<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC \"-//w3c//dtd html 4.0 transitional//en\">\n<html>\n  <head>\n    <meta content=\"text/html; charset=windows-1252\"\n      http-equiv=\"Content-Type\">\n    <meta name=\"Content-Type\" content=\"text/html; charset=iso-8859-1\">\n    <meta name=\"GENERATOR\" content=\"Mozilla/4.71 (Macintosh; I; PPC)\n      [Netscape]\">\n    <title>INF231: User Interface Design and Evaluation</title>\n  </head>\n  <body style=\"background-color: rgb(153, 204, 255);\">\n    <center>\n      <h1 align=\"left\"><strong></strong><br>\n      </h1>\n      <h1 style=\"text-align: right;\"><small><a style=\"font-family:\n            Arial;\"\nhref=\"http://www.ics.uci.edu/community/news/articles/view_article?id=399\">btw</a><span\n            style=\"font-family: Arial;\">...</span></small><br>\n      </h1>\n      <h1 align=\"right\"><font size=\"4\"><a\n            href=\"http://www.ics.uci.edu/informatics/news/news_2007.php#kobsa_hci\"><font\n              face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><br>\n            </font></a></font></h1>\n      <h1><font size=\"4\"><font size=\"6\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n            sans-serif\">INF231: User Interface Design and Evaluation<br>\n          </font></font></h1>\n    </center>\n    <center>\n      <h3><font size=\"4\"> <font face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>Instructor:\nAlfred\nKobsa\n\n\n\n\n              <br>\n              (email: &lt;last name&gt; @ uci.edu)</b></font><br>\n        </font></h3>\n    </center>\n    <center>\n      <p>&nbsp; </p>\n    </center>\n    <center>\n      <p align=\"left\"><font size=\"4\"><strong><font face=\"Arial,\n              Helvetica, sans-serif\">Disclaimer:</font></strong><font\n            face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"> These are guidelines\n            are intended to help students plan their work in this class.\n            However, the instructor does reserve the right to make\n            changes if needed, including students' signups.<br>\n          </font></font></p>\n    </center>\n    <p><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>General\n          Educational Aims: </b>This course provides an introduction to\n        the field of human-computer interaction (HCI), with an emphasis\n        on user interface design and evaluation. Students will learn\n        methods for user needs and task analysis as well as interface\n        testing, and guidelines for good user interface design.</font></p>\n    <p><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>Requirements</b>:\n        Graduate level. Students should have used computers and\n        different software for at least one year<font size=\"+2\">&#9786;</font>.\n      </font> </p>\n    <p><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>Format</b>:\n        Lecture by instructor, quarter-long term project <span\n          style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"></span>with internal and\n        external clients, project presentations.</font></p>\n    <p><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong>This\n          class vs. INF232:</strong> This class will focus on <span\n          style=\"font-style: italic;\">practical</span> HCI skills and\n        training. It will cater to the needs of master students and of\n        those PhD students who are mostly interested in the practical\n        aspects of HCI. <br>\n        The INF 232 class will instead cater to Ph.D. students who\n        intend to focus on HCI as a <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">research\n\n\n\n\n          topic</span> (MS students who are particularly qualified and\n        theoretically inclined can also be admitted). It will focus on\n        influential HCI literature, HCI theory, and current research\n        questions. A familiarity with basic HCI topics and methods will\n        be assumed.</font></p>\n    <p><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>Time and\n          Location</b>: &nbsp; <br>\n      </font></p>\n    <p><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\n\n\n\n        <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Lecture</span>: MW\n        2:00-3:20pm, <a\n          href=\"http://www.classrooms.uci.edu/GAC/MSTB.html\">MSTB 110</a>.\n        Starts on Oct. 2<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><br>\n        </span></font></p>\n    <p><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">The <span\n          style=\"font-style: italic;\">discussions</span> are mostly for\n        project meetings, sometimes with the customer. Register for one\n        discussion/project only. The instructor reserves the right\n        though to reassign students to ensure suitable head counts and\n        skill sets.<br>\n      </font></p>\n    <p><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span\n              style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Discussion 1</span>\n            (code 37341): </span></strong></font><font size=\"4\"\n        face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\">M 9-10:50am <a\n              href=\"http://www.classrooms.uci.edu/GAC/MSTB.html\">MSTB\n              110</a></span></strong></font><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n        Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong></strong></font><font size=\"4\"\n        face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><a\n              href=\"http://www.classrooms.uci.edu/GAC/ICS.html\"><span\n                style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"></span></a></span></strong></font><font\n        size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\"> and </span></strong></font><font\n        size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n              Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight:\n                  normal;\">F 9-10:50<font face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n                    sans-serif\">a</font>m <a\n                    href=\"http://www.classrooms.uci.edu/GAC/DBH.html\">DBH\n\n\n\n\n                    1431</a></span></strong></font>. Starts on Oct. 6</span></strong></font><font\n        size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\"></span></strong></font><font\n        size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong></strong></font><font\n        size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong></strong></font><br>\n      <font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\"></span></strong></font></p>\n    <div style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n        Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight:\n            normal;\">Project 1: </span></strong></font><font size=\"4\"\n        face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Facilitating job search with\n        social support and gamification (Naomi Sugie, UCI, nsugie at\n        uci.edu)</font><br>\n      <blockquote> <font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n              style=\"font-weight: normal;\"></span></strong></font><font\n          size=\"-1\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n              style=\"font-weight: normal;\">This project aims for the\n              design of a user interface for an application that assists\n              released convicts in finding jobs. Special attention\n              should be paid to the inclusion of real-time job\n              information, peer-based social support, a GPS-based\n              \"check-in\" function when at potential employers, and the\n              integration of gamification elements to sustain user\n              engagement over time.&nbsp; Students should develop early\n              designs for the different system components, solicit\n              feedback from the target audience, and consider this\n              feedback during the development of an interactive mockup.\n              Students should decide whether a standalone Android app or\n              a browser extension for Facebook is the better\n              approach.&nbsp; </span></strong></font><br>\n        <font size=\"-1\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n              style=\"font-weight: normal;\"></span></strong></font></blockquote>\n    </div>\n    <p><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span\n              style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Discussion 2</span>\n            (code 37342): Tu 2-3:50pm</span></strong></font><font\n        size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong></strong></font><font\n        size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\"> </span></strong></font><font\n        size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n              Helvetica, sans-serif\"><a\n                href=\"http://www.classrooms.uci.edu/GAC/MSTB.html\">MSTB\n                110</a></font> and Th </span></strong></font><font\n        size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n              Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight:\n                  normal;\">2-3:50pm <a\n                    href=\"http://www.classrooms.uci.edu/GAC/SSL.html\">SSL152</a></span></strong></font><font\n              size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong></strong></font><font\n              size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n                  style=\"font-weight: normal;\"></span></strong></font><font\n              size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n                  style=\"font-weight: normal;\"></span></strong></font>.</span></strong></font><strong><strong><font\n            size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n                style=\"font-weight: normal;\"> Starts on Oct. 3</span></strong></font><font\n            size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n                style=\"font-weight: normal;\"></span></strong></font><font\n            size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong></strong></font><font\n            size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong></strong></font><br>\n        </strong></strong></p>\n    <div style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><strong><strong><font size=\"4\"\n            face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n                style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Project 2: </span></strong></font><font\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\" size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n            Helvetica, sans-serif\">Usability design for chatbot in a\n            group collaboration scenario </font><font\n            style=\"font-weight: normal;\" size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n            Helvetica, sans-serif\">(Dakuo Wang, IBM Research, dakuow1 at\n            uci.edu)</font><br>\n        </strong></strong>\n      <blockquote><strong><strong> <font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n              Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight:\n                  normal;\"></span></strong></font><font size=\"4\"\n              face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n                  style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><font size=\"-1\">The aim\n                    of the project is to look into the usefulness of an\n                    intelligent agent (chatbox) in a textual group\n                    collaboration, with the aim of improving the\n                    collaboration. The topic can be approached from\n                    different perspectives, and it is up to the student\n                    team to decide whether it is practical to achieve\n                    any or all of these goals:</font></span></strong></font></strong><strong><font\n              size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong><span\n                  style=\"font-weight: normal;\"></span></strong></font></strong></strong><br>\n        <strong><strong><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n              sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"></span></strong></font></strong></strong>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong><strong><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n                  sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><font\n                        size=\"-1\">It has to start with an understanding\n                        or exploration of what the needs are in a group\n                        collaboration scenario. What kinds of\n                        collaborative tasks the group might need a\n                        chatbot's help, and how the chatbot can be\n                        designed to help. Given this is a class, the\n                        target user groups in this context could be\n                        student teams. </font></span></strong></font></strong></strong></li>\n          <li><strong><strong><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n                  sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><font\n                        size=\"-1\">It can be from the system design\n                        perspective. That the students from an\n                        engineering background to actually build a\n                        prototype using the existing programming\n                        frameworks or AI libraries (e.g., IBM,\n                        Microsoft, Google, or Facebook). In the target\n                        use case, this prototype chatbot can respond to\n                        or proactively intervene the group's\n                        behavior.&nbsp; </font></span></strong></font></strong></strong></li>\n          <li><strong><strong><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n                  sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><font\n                        size=\"-1\">&nbsp;It can be a Wizard of Oz study.\n                        With a script, a student plays as the\n                        chatbot/agent to interact or intervene a group's\n                        behavior.</font></span></strong></font></strong></strong></li>\n          <li><strong><strong><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n                  sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><font\n                        size=\"-1\">&nbsp;The study design can be a\n                        in-situ experiment or a lab experiment. </font></span></strong></font></strong></strong></li>\n          <li><strong><strong><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n                  sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><font\n                        size=\"-1\">&nbsp;It can also consist with survey\n                        or interview study.</font></span></strong></font></strong></strong></li>\n        </ul>\n      </blockquote>\n    </div>\n    <p><strong><strong><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n            sans-serif\"> </font><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n            sans-serif\"><strong></strong></font></strong></strong><font\n        style=\"font-weight: bold;\" size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n        sans-serif\">Required readings: </font></p>\n    <ul style=\"font-weight: normal;\">\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Kathy\n          Baxter, Catherine Courage, and Kelly Caine (2015):\n          Understanding Your Users: A Practical Guide to User Research\n          Methods. </font><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n          sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">2nd enhanced\n            edition.</span> </font><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n          Helvetica, sans-serif\">Morgan Kaufmann. ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/compare.cgi?dispCurr=USD&amp;id=53773&amp;isbn=9780128002322&amp;location=10000&amp;thetime=20160905224407&amp;author=&amp;title=&amp;state=CA\">978-0-12-800232-2</a>.\n          Also <a\nhref=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780128002322000018\">online</a>\n          (free access from the UCI domain), </font><font size=\"4\"\n          face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><a\nhref=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/book/understanding-your-users-enhanced/id1000818277?mt=11\">iBook</a>,\n          <a\nhref=\"http://www.amazon.com/Understanding-Your-Users-Interactive-Technologies-ebook/dp/B00Y82LGZO/ref=sr_1_1?s=digital-text&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1441959212&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=Understanding+your+users\">Kindle</a></font>,\n        <font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><a\nhref=\"https://play.google.com/store/books/details/Kathy_Baxter_Understanding_Your_Users?id=l9-cBAAAQBAJ\">Google</a></font></li>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Jeffrey\n          Rubin and Dana Chisnell (2008): Handbook of Usability Testing:\n          How to Plan, Design, and Conduct Effective Tests. <span\n            style=\"font-style: italic;\">2nd edition</span>. Wiley, ISBN\n          <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/submitNew.cgi?query=978-0470185483&amp;type=ISBN&amp;location=10000&amp;state=CA&amp;dispCurr=USD\">978-0470185483</a>.\n          Also as <a\nhref=\"http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-1118080408.html\">e-book</a>\n          (DRM) or for <a\nhref=\"http://www.amazon.com/Handbook-Usability-Testing-Effective-ebook/dp/B008L03ZOY/ref=sr_1_1_title_1_kin?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1379188186&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=Rubin+Handbook+of+Usability+Testing\">Kindle</a>\n          and from </font><font size=\"4\"><font face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n            sans-serif\">a <a\n              href=\"http://antpac.lib.uci.edu/search/r?SEARCH=%22Informatics%20231%22\">reserve</a>\n            in the Ayala Science Library.</font></font><span\n          style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><font size=\"4\"><font face=\"Arial,\n              Helvetica, sans-serif\"><a href=\"http://postyourbook.com/\"><span\n                  style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"></span></a></font></font>\n        </span> </li>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">D. K.\n          Farkas J. B. and Farkas (2000): G<i>uidelines for Designing\n            Web Navigation. Technical Communication</i> 4(2000),\n          341-358.<span style=\"font-style: italic;\"> </span><a\nhref=\"http://www.ics.uci.edu/%7Ekobsa/courses/ICS104/lit/Farkas&amp;Farkas-TC.pdf\">Electronic\n\n\n\n\n            version</a><i> (for class usage only!)</i></font></li>\n      <span style=\"font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span\n          style=\"font-style: italic;\"> </span></span>\n    </ul>\n    <font size=\"4\"><font face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"></font></font>\n    <p style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n        sans-serif\">Further readings at your leisure: </font> </p>\n    <ul style=\"font-weight: normal;\">\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">B.\n          Shneiderman, C. Plaisant, M. Cohen, S. Jacobs, N. Elmqvist, N.\n          Diakopoulos (2015): Designing the User Interface: Strategies\n          for Effective Human-Computer Interaction. Sixth Edition,\n          Addison-Wesley, ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/submitNew.cgi?query=978-0134380384&amp;type=ISBN&amp;location=10000&amp;state=CA&amp;dispCurr=USD\">978-0134380384</a></font></li>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Carol M.\n          Barnum (2010): Usability Testing Essentials. Ready,\n          Set...Test! Morgan Kaufmann. ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/submitNew.cgi?query=978-0123750921&amp;type=ISBN&amp;location=10000&amp;state=CA&amp;dispCurr=USD\">978-0123750921</a></font></li>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Joseph S.\n          Dumas and Beth A. Loring (2008): </font><font size=\"4\"\n          face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Moderating Usability\n          Tests: Principles and Practices for Interacting. Morgan\n          Kaufmann ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/submitNew.cgi?query=978-0123739339&amp;type=ISBN&amp;location=10000&amp;state=CA&amp;dispCurr=USD\">978-0123739339</a></font></li>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Jeff\n          Johnson (2014): Designing with the Mind in Mind: Simple Guide\n          to Understanding User Interface Design Guidelines. 2nd\n          edition. Morgan Kaufmann. ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/submitNew.cgi?query=978-0124079144&amp;type=ISBN&amp;location=10000&amp;state=CA&amp;dispCurr=USD\">978-0124079144</a>.\n          For Kindle.</font></li>\n    </ul>\n    <font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><a\nhref=\"http://www.amazon.com/Designing-Mind-Understanding-Interface-ebook/dp/B003H3IOXM/ref=tmm_kin_title_0\"></a></font>\n    <ul style=\"font-weight: normal;\">\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Jim\n          Thatcher et al. (2006): Web Accessibility: Web Standards and\n          Regulatory Compliance. Friends of Ed. ISBN 978-1590-59638-8. <a\n            href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4302-0188-5\">Electronic\n\n\n\n\n            edition</a> (free from within UCI domain).</font></li>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Caroline\n          Jarrett and </font><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n          sans-serif\">Gerry Gaffney (2008): </font><font size=\"4\"\n          face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Forms that Work: Designing\n          Web Forms for Usability. Morgan Kaufmann, ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/submitNew.cgi?query=978-1558607101&amp;type=ISBN&amp;location=10000&amp;state=CA&amp;dispCurr=USD\">978-1558607101</a></font></li>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Chris\n          Nodder (2013): Evil by Design: Interaction design to lead us\n          into temptation. </font><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n          Helvetica, sans-serif\">Wiley, ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www3.addall.com/New/submitNew.cgi?query=978-1118422144&amp;type=ISBN&amp;location=10000&amp;state=CA&amp;dispCurr=USD\">978-1118422144</a></font></li>\n    </ul>\n    <ul style=\"font-weight: normal;\">\n      <span style=\"font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"></span>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Tom Tullis\n          and Bill Albert (2013): Measuring the User Experience:\n          Collecting, Analyzing, and Presenting Usability Metrics. 2nd\n          edition: Morgan Kaufmann, ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/submitNew.cgi?query=978-0124157811&amp;type=ISBN&amp;location=10000&amp;state=CA&amp;dispCurr=USD\">978-0124157811</a>.\n          Also <a\n            href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/book/9780124157811\">online</a>\n          (free from within the UCI domain)<br>\n        </font></li>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Jonathan\n          Lazar et al. (2010): Research Methods in Human-Computer\n          Interaction. Wiley. </font><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n          Helvetica, sans-serif\">ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/submitNew.cgi?query=978-0470-72337-1&amp;type=ISBN&amp;location=10000&amp;state=CA&amp;dispCurr=USD\">978-0470-72337-1</a></font></li>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Judy Olson\n          and Wendy Kellogg, (2014). Ways of Knowing in HCI. Springer.\n          ISBN <a\nhref=\"http://www.addall.com/New/compare.cgi?dispCurr=USD&amp;id=53859&amp;isbn=9781493903771&amp;location=10000&amp;thetime=20160905225601&amp;author=&amp;title=&amp;state=CA\">978-1493-90377-1</a>.\n          Also <a\n            href=\"http://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-1-4939-0378-8\">online</a>\n          (free from within the UCI domain)<br>\n        </font></li>\n      <span style=\"font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"></span>\n      <li><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><a\nhref=\"https://www.interaction-design.org/literature/book/the-encyclopedia-of-human-computer-interaction-2nd-ed\">The\nEncyclopedia\n\n\n\n\n            of Human-Computer Interaction</a>, 2nd Ed. <br>\n        </font></li>\n    </ul>\n    <font size=\"4\"><font face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"></font></font>\n    <p style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n        sans-serif\">Grading: &nbsp;&nbsp; </font><font\n        style=\"font-weight: normal;\" face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><font\n          size=\"4\">50% for </font></font><font size=\"4\" face=\"Arial,\n        Helvetica, sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">project\n\n\n\n          (partially peer\n          evaluation)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><br\n          style=\"font-weight: normal;\">\n        <span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n          &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n          &nbsp; 45% for final exam on </span><span style=\"color:\n          rgb(204, 0, 0); font-weight: normal;\"><span\n            style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><font face=\"Arial, Helvetica,\n              sans-serif\">Monday</font> Dec 1<font face=\"Arial,\n              Helvetica, sans-serif\">1</font> at 10:30-<font\n              face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">12</font>